EPODE IV.

A violent attack on some freedman, who moved the wrath os Horace and of the citizens by his display and arrogance. ‘A little while ago flogged as a slave: now with a fine estate in Campania, a pony-carriage on the Appian way, and a seat at spectacles among the “equites ”! With what face do we fit out fleets against Sextus Pompeius and his run-

away slaves, if we let a man of the same stamp hold the rank of ¹ “tribunus militum ” ‘? ’

We can hardly doubt that the Epode was aimed at some real person. ¹¹
